additional_toughts_1b: Moving objects was basically equivalent in all versions ( I don't think it would have made a big difference with converged, 1spp or Method B), but choosing colour was difficult because of the grainyness
additional_toughts_1c: Much easier to change the colour with this render method, otherwise still basically the same (also it is hard to compare to 1spp, when I never did these particular tasks in 1spp)
additional_toughts_1d: This was distracting. In the kitchen the bell pepper was easier to change colour on, but moving was weird because everything was blurry, in the living room moving was easier because there was high contrast between the glass and the table, but changing the horse, again was very difficult. Liked this method the least so far
additional_toughts_2b: Didn't really notice a difference in Tile Size settings. Likes low tile quality though as that meant updates were being rended quickly. This was only annoying during long periods of moving things
additional_toughts_2c: I played around with the tile quality a bit. For moving small objects I prefer higher values like 64, but for moving big objects like the table 4 was better, no matter which tile size I picked
additional_toughts_2d: The tasks were super different. Moving the table was a lot easier because there was good contrast, I'd say it was the best of the three methods. Changing the cooker was also the best so far, but moving the home decor, was weird to see, and felt a lot less clean than other methods
additional_toughts_3b: Since this changes the entire scene for the most part, the one downside to spp was that it takes longer to update, because it starts at the light source. Other than that I don't think there is that big of a difference between doing it in 1spp, converged or this method. Also the UI for the light makes no sense
additional_toughts_3c: In the kitchen this method was better, still took longer to render the whole picture, and was definitely better than 1spp for the small light, because of colour clarity. Living room was worse, it took a long time to update. I don't think I would have minded doing this in 1spp though, especially if I didn't know this method existed
additional_toughts_3d: Definitely the best method for these large scale light changes. it was the only one that felt reponsive and fast where I had proper control of the colour as well
preference_reason:
This method felt best for moving things with high contrast and bigger objects (mostly in the living room) and changing light. For moving smaller objects with less contrast I prefer method C though. In general I would say it depends on what I want to do, for small detail work I'd go with method C for big scene renderings and adjustments method A.
For the ranking below I will assume that I want to make bigger changes, since that is more what I do
